<h2>Deep Analysis: PI-Forward, AI-Native Research Administration</h2>
<p>Your insight identifies a genuine market gap. Let me synthesize what I found.</p>
<h3>The Workday Problem is Real and Severe</h3>
<p>The data is damning:
- <strong><a href="https://www.studlife.com/news/2025/12/10/breaking-down-workdays-265-million-cost">Washington University: $266 million</a></strong> for Workday implementation
- <strong><a href="https://tonemadison.com/articles/workday-and-the-excesses-of-higher-ed-efficiency-consultants/">University of Wisconsin: $172 million</a></strong> (Huron + Workday combined)
- Another university: <strong>$340 million</strong> with grants stuck in processing limbo
- At UW Seattle, <strong>59% of faculty considering leaving</strong> and <strong>50% reduced grant applications</strong> due to Workday problems</p>
<p>The fundamental issue: Workday was built for corporate business, not <a href="https://www.washington.edu/research/workday-finance-research/">research universities with complex grant-funded operations</a>.</p>
<h3>The Conceptual Overlap You Identified</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>What PIs at Rich Institutions Need</th>
<th>What Global Institutions Need</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Simple interface to complex backends</td>
<td>Affordable systems (&lt;$200M!)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Natural language grant queries</td>
<td>Works with limited IT infrastructure</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>"Can I afford X?" projections</td>
<td>Minimal training required</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Compliance in plain English</td>
<td>Connection to global funding</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>The common thread: Both groups want SIMPLICITY. Workday solves for enterprise compliance. Users need clarity, speed, and accessibility.</strong></p>
<h3>Current Landscape Gaps</h3>
<p>The <a href="https://www.instrumentl.com/blog/post-award-grant-management-software">existing grant management tools</a> fall into two camps:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Enterprise behemoths</strong> (Workday, SAP): $100M+ implementations, designed for finance departments</li>
<li><strong>Nonprofit-focused tools</strong> (Instrumentl at $499/mo, AmpliFund): Grant-seeking focused, not PI-workflow focused</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Nothing exists that is:</strong>
- AI-first (natural language primary interface)
- PI-centered (not admin/finance centered)
- Globally accessible (works in Kenya as well as California)
- Open source / radically affordable</p>
<h3>The Africa Context</h3>
<p>The <a href="https://scienceforafrica.foundation/africa-research-management-capacity-strengthening-programme">REMACS Programme</a> is building "Good Research Management Practice Standards" from scratch because African institutions can't access enterprise systems. <a href="https://www.carnegie.org/programs/higher-education-and-research-in-africa/">Carnegie invested $134M (2010-2019)</a> in African research capacity. This infrastructure gap is a massive opportunity.</p>
<h3>The AI-Native Advantage</h3>
<p>Current <a href="https://opengrants.io/best-ai-for-grant-writing/">AI grant tools</a> focus on <strong>writing</strong> grants. Almost nothing addresses the <strong>management</strong> side with AI:</p>
<pre><code>PI asks: &quot;Can I hire a summer student on my R01?&quot;

What happens in Workday:
1. Navigate to Grants Worklet
2. Find cost center
3. Decode worktags
4. Check encumbrances
5. Calculate available balance
6. Cross-reference with grant terms
7. Email grants office to confirm
[Time: 30-60 minutes]

What should happen:
&quot;Yes. Your R01-GM123456 has $47,230 unencumbered. 
A summer student (10 weeks, $6,000 stipend + $1,200 benefits + 55% F&amp;A) 
costs ~$11,160. You'd have $36,070 remaining through 8/31/2026. 
Note: This grant prohibits international students without prior approval.&quot;
[Time: 5 seconds]
</code></pre>
<h3>Proposed System Architecture</h3>
<p><strong>Core Philosophy: Simple data + Smart AI &gt; Complex data + Dumb interface</strong></p>
<p><strong>Data Model (Radically Simple):</strong></p>
<pre><code>Grants:     funding_source, amount, start_date, end_date, restrictions
People:     who works on what grants, at what %
Expenses:   what was spent, when, on what category
Projections: planned future spending
Rules:      sponsor requirements, institutional policies
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Feature Progression:</strong></p>
