<td>For routing only</td>
<td>✗</td>
<td>✗</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>University Dashboards</td>
<td>✗</td>
<td>✗</td>
<td>✗</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>This Project</td>
<td>✓</td>
<td>✓</td>
<td>✓</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>The moat isn't "better AI" - it's "comprehensive proposal memory with AI query."</strong></p>
<p>Nobody is doing this. Enterprise systems track proposals for compliance routing, not for PI utility. Spendlab only sees the world after funding.</p>
<hr />
<h3>Revised Data Model</h3>
<p>Proposals become the <strong>first-class citizen</strong>, not awards:</p>
<pre><code class="language-sql">-- The core entity is now the proposal
proposals (
  id, user_id,
  sponsor, program, mechanism,        -- NIH R01, NSF CAREER, etc.
  title, abstract,
  specific_aims,                      -- extracted or entered
  full_document,                      -- stored for AI querying
  timeline_milestones (jsonb),        -- what you promised when
  personnel_plan (jsonb),             -- who you said you'd hire
  key_methods,                        -- approaches committed to
  submitted_date, deadline,
  status (draft|submitted|under_review|scored|funded|declined|withdrawn)
)

-- Outcomes include both funded and unfunded
proposal_outcomes (
  proposal_id,
  outcome (funded|declined|not_discussed),
  score, percentile,
  critique_summary,                   -- uploaded review
  amount_funded,                      -- may differ from requested
  budget_modifications                -- what got cut
)

-- Awards derive FROM proposals
awards (
  proposal_id,                        -- linked to source proposal
  grant_number, account_number,
  actual_amount, start_date, end_date,
  adjusted_budget (jsonb),            -- post-cut budget
  status (active|nce|closed)
)

-- Spending tracks against award
spending_updates (
  award_id, date, category, amount
)
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3>Example Queries This Enables</h3>
<p><strong>Portfolio queries:</strong>
- "How many proposals have I submitted this fiscal year?"
- "What's my funding rate over the last 3 years?"
- "Show me all declined proposals that I haven't resubmitted"</p>
<p><strong>Commitment queries:</strong>
- "What milestones did I promise for Year 2 of my R01?"
- "Did I commit to any international travel in this grant?"
- "Which of my grants mentions single-cell sequencing?"</p>
<p><strong>Decision queries:</strong>
- "Can I hire a summer student?" → checks budget + personnel plan
- "Can I buy a $20K sequencer?" → checks equipment budget + proposed methods
- "Is pivoting to phage work consistent with my funded aims?"</p>
<p><strong>Compliance queries:</strong>
- "Has my scope changed enough to require NIH notification?"
- "Am I on track for my Year 1 milestones?"
- "Which grant is best suited for this new collaboration?"</p>
<hr />
<h3>Revised MVP Scope</h3>
<p><strong>Phase 1: Proposal Portfolio</strong>
- Add proposals (manual entry, document upload, paste)
- Track status through lifecycle
- Store outcomes (scores, critiques)
- Basic search across proposals</p>
<p><strong>Phase 2: Award Tracking</strong>
- Link funded proposals to active awards
- Budget tracking at category level
- Balance queries</p>
<p><strong>Phase 3: AI Query Layer</strong>
- Natural language queries against proposal content
- Commitment extraction and comparison
- Cross-proposal search
- Decision support ("Can I do X?")</p>
<hr />
<p>This is a fundamentally different product than I was describing. It's <strong>your research funding memory</strong> - everything you applied for, what you promised, what got funded, and whether your current decisions are consistent with your commitments.</p>
