<td>Core + basic procurement</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Lab in Kenya</td>
<td>Core only (manual spending entry)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>EU institution</td>
<td>Core + EU vendor integrations</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Everyone gets the core value (proposals, awards, AI queries). Depth is available but not required.</p>
<hr />
<h3>The Strategic Question</h3>
<p>Is item-level procurement tracking:</p>
<p><strong>A) Core to the value proposition?</strong>
- Without it, spending is manual entry that drifts
- The "shadow spreadsheet" problem persists
- Real automation requires real data</p>
<p><strong>B) A powerful enhancement?</strong>
- Most PIs would be happy with category-level tracking
- Item-level is nice-to-have
- Keeps scope manageable</p>
<p><strong>C) Something in between?</strong>
- Build procurement-ready architecture
- Support item-level when available
- Gracefully degrade to manual when not</p>
<p>I lean toward <strong>C</strong> - design for item-level, but don't require it. The architecture should support a reagent-level view when the data exists, but still work when a PI just says "I spent about $12K on supplies this quarter."</p>
<hr />
<p>What's your instinct? Is item-level tracking essential to solving the problem you're experiencing, or is the proposal/commitment memory the more critical piece?</p></div></div><button class="expand-btn">Show more</button></div></div>
