<h2>Tiered Architecture: Intelligence Layer First</h2>
<p>You're right. The foundation should be universally applicable, independent of institutional requirements. Here's the tiered approach:</p>
<hr />
<h3>The Tiers</h3>
<pre><code>┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  TIER 3: INSTITUTIONAL INTEGRATION                              │
│  Workday/Banner • HR Systems • ELN/LIMS • SSO                   │
│  (For institutions that need/want connectivity)                 │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  TIER 2: PROCUREMENT &amp; INVENTORY                                │
│  Item-level tracking • Orders • Inventory • Vendors             │
│  (Native or integrate Lab Spend, Quartzy, etc.)                 │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  TIER 1: DETAILED FINANCIAL TRACKING                            │
│  Budget categories • Personnel detail • Burn rate • Projections │
│  (Structured data entry, statement uploads)                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  TIER 0: INTELLIGENCE LAYER  ← FOUNDATION                       │
│  Proposals • Awards • Commitments • People • Outputs • AI Query │
│  (Works anywhere, no integrations, no institutional buy-in)     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3>Tier 0: The Intelligence Layer (Foundation)</h3>
<p><strong>The question it answers:</strong> <em>"What did I apply for? What did I promise? Can I do X?"</em></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Component</th>
<th>What It Does</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Proposals</strong></td>
<td>Track everything you submitted (funded or not)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Awards</strong></td>
<td>Active grants linked to source proposals</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Commitments</strong></td>
<td>AI-extracted aims, milestones, deliverables</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>People</strong></td>
<td>Your team, their roles, which grants</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Outputs</strong></td>
<td>Papers, data, presentations linked to grants</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>AI Query</strong></td>
<td>Natural language access to all of the above</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Data input:</strong> Manual entry, document upload (PDF/Word), AI extraction</p>
<p><strong>No dependencies:</strong>
- No Workday
- No institutional systems
- No IT approval
- No enterprise sales cycle</p>
<p><strong>Works for:</strong>
- PI at WashU frustrated with Workday
- PI at small liberal arts college with no admin
- Researcher in Kenya with just a laptop
- New investigator building first portfolio</p>
<hr />
<h3>What Tier 0 Enables</h3>
<pre><code>&quot;Upload my R01&quot;
→ AI extracts: Specific Aims, Budget, Timeline, Key Personnel
→ Stored as queryable knowledge

&quot;This got funded for $1.1M starting September&quot;
→ Creates active award linked to proposal
→ Basic budget tracking begins

&quot;What did I promise in Year 2?&quot;
→ AI retrieves from stored proposal:
   &quot;Year 2 milestones:
    - Complete enrollment (n=100)
    - Finish Aim 1 analysis
    - Begin Aim 2 interventions
    - Submit first manuscript&quot;

&quot;Can I hire a summer student?&quot;
→ AI checks: Budget remaining, personnel plan, restrictions
→ &quot;Based on your proposal, you budgeted for 'undergraduate 
    research assistants' under Aim 2. You have ~$85K remaining 
    over 18 months. A summer student fits.&quot;

&quot;Show me all my declined proposals&quot;
→ List with scores, critiques, resubmission status
→ &quot;You have 3 declined R01s. One was resubmitted and funded.
    Two are candidates for revision.&quot;

&quot;Generate my progress report outline&quot;
→ AI drafts from: proposal aims + logged outputs + milestones
→ &quot;Aim 1: Proposed to characterize X. You've published 2 papers
    on this topic and generated dataset Y...&quot;
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h3>Why Tier 0 First?</h3>
<p><strong>1. Universally applicable</strong></p>
<p>Every researcher needs this regardless of institution, country, or budget. The problems are the same:
- What did I promise?
- Can I afford X?
- Am I on track?
- What have I applied for?</p>
<p><strong>2. Zero dependencies</strong></p>
<p>No Workday API. No institutional approval. No IT involvement. A PI can sign up and get value in 30 minutes.</p>
<p><strong>3. Solves the core pain</strong></p>
<p>The <a href="https://thefdp.org/demonstrations-resources/faculty-workload-survey/">FDP surveys</a> show 42% of research time goes to administration. The biggest chunks:
- Figuring out what you can/can't do → <strong>Tier 0 solves</strong>
- Remembering commitments → <strong>Tier 0 solves</strong>
- Generating reports → <strong>Tier 0 solves</strong>
- Processing transactions → Tier 1-2 solve</p>
<p><strong>4. Natural upgrade path</strong></p>
<p>Tier 0 users who want more precision add Tier 1. Labs wanting item-level tracking add Tier 2. Institutions wanting connectivity add Tier 3.</p>
<p>The data model expands; the foundation doesn't change.</p>
